function\">withParsedBody</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token variable\">$parsedBody</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n\t\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">;</span>\n\t<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span>\n<span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre></div>\n<h2>Happily ever after</h2>\n<p>With all this set up, any request handler that needs to parse the request body is accompanied by a class that describes\nits schema and validation constraints, and further represents the request body. The handler itself does not have to worry\nabout the parsing nor validation any more, and can focus on its actual job instead. If you ask me, that's a very nice\nseparation of responsibilities.</p>\n<p>What do you think about it? Can you see any weak points in this solution? Do you use anything like that? I'm looking\nforward to your comments!</p>","timeToRead":7,"frontmatter":{"legacyId":null,"title":"Body parser middleware that has your back","slug":"body-parser-middleware-that-has-your-back","datetime":"2020-01-28T14:00:00.000Z","cupsOfCoffee":4,"perex":"If you've ever implemented an HTTP API in PHP, you probably know that there's one thing you have to do over and over and over: parse the request body and validate the resulting structure. Now that we have PSR-15, let's use a middleware for that!","tags":["api","frameworkless","http","middlewares","php","rest","software-architecture"]},"fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/jiripudil.cz/jiripudil.cz/src/blog/posts/2020-01-28-body-parser-middleware-that-has-your-back.md"}},"pageContext":{"slug":"body-parser-middleware-that-has-your-back"}},"staticQueryHashes":["193688581","2068912127","3504401423"]}